 engagement, those in the lower reaches of stratified society are left largely on the outside looking in-and that all too easily becomes a self-perpetuating cycle. Public Engagement for Public Education speaks to the potential for students, parents, community members, and civic leaders to join forces and create more equitable schooling. Such engagement can expand access to quality educational pathways which in turn paves the way to a stronger voice in society and the promise of the American dream. If segments of society are blocked access to those pathways, the book argues, nothing less than the health of American democracy is at stake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCommunity and schoolzUnited States. 0aEducationzUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aPublic schoolszUnited StatesxCitizen participation. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aOrr, Marion, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRogers, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477638740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804776387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804776387.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles